# Zitadel bootstrap — `<project-name>` (2.0.0 candidate)

Post-deploy bootstrap recipe for the Zitadel IdP introduced by B.8.7. The chart
does the heavy lifting (first org + admin + machine user via its `setupJob`); this
doc covers the **FirstInstance contract**, the **OIDC client registration** recipe
(Admin/Management API), and the **JWT signing-key rotation** posture. All
credentials are placeholders — **no secret value is committed** (FR-B87-021).

> All endpoints, env-var names, and rotation cadences below were verified LIVE
> 2026-06-02 against the upstream Zitadel source (evidence.md P-18..P-21). They
> are NOT fabricated (Article III.4).

## Bootstrap stages (chart-native, ADR-B87-003)

1. **Stage 1 — initJob** (Helm hook weight 1): creates the `zitadel` DB schema,
   user, and grants on the B.8.5 `fsm-db` Postgres 17 instance. Runs before the
   main Deployment.
2. **Stage 2 — setupJob** (Helm hook weight 2, after initJob): runs `zitadel
   setup` with the `FirstInstance` config from `values-forge.yaml.tmpl` →
   creates the first organisation, the human admin, and the machine user
   (`iam-admin`, IAM_OWNER). It writes the machine user's PAT into a **K8s Secret
   auto-named after the machine `Username`** (e.g. derived from `iam-admin`).
3. **Stage 3 — Admin API recipe** (below): use the machine-user PAT to register
   the OIDC client application. This is a documented post-deploy recipe, NOT a
   shipped K8s Job (the subtree stays minimal).

## FirstInstance contract

The chart wires FirstInstance under `zitadel.configmapConfig.FirstInstance` in
`values-forge.yaml.tmpl` (evidence.md P-18 / Finding 8). The underlying Zitadel
binary also accepts the equivalent **top-level** `ZITADEL_FIRSTINSTANCE_*` env
mirrors (live `cmd/setup/steps.yaml`, P-11) — relevant if you bypass the chart:

| Env var | Settable? | Notes |
|---------|-----------|-------|
| `ZITADEL_FIRSTINSTANCE_INSTANCENAME` | ✅ user | instance name |
| `ZITADEL_FIRSTINSTANCE_ORG_NAME` | ✅ user | first org name |
| `ZITADEL_FIRSTINSTANCE_ORG_HUMAN_USERNAME` | ✅ user | human admin username |
| `ZITADEL_FIRSTINSTANCE_ORG_HUMAN_PASSWORD` | ✅ user (env/secret only — never committed) | initial admin password |
| `ZITADEL_FIRSTINSTANCE_ORG_HUMAN_PASSWORDCHANGEREQUIRED` | ✅ user | force change on first login |
| `ZITADEL_FIRSTINSTANCE_ORG_MACHINE_MACHINE_USERNAME` | ✅ user | machine user (service account) |
| `ZITADEL_FIRSTINSTANCE_MACHINEKEYPATH` | ⛔ **CHART-MANAGED — do NOT set** | setting it manually is unsupported and will fail the deploy (P-18) |
| `ZITADEL_FIRSTINSTANCE_PATPATH` | ⛔ **CHART-MANAGED — do NOT set** | the chart auto-generates the PAT into a K8s Secret |
| `ZITADEL_FIRSTINSTANCE_LOGINCLIENTPATPATH` | ⛔ **CHART-MANAGED — do NOT set** | login-client PAT, chart-managed |

**Note** (P-18 / Finding 8): under the Helm chart, prefer the YAML form
(`configmapConfig.FirstInstance.*`) over the env mirrors. `MachineKeyPath`,
`PatPath`, and `LoginClientPatPath` are managed automatically by the chart;
setting them manually "is not supported and will cause the deployment to fail."

## Retrieve the machine-user PAT

The chart `setupJob` writes the `iam-admin` PAT into a K8s Secret named after the
machine user's `Username`. Read it (placeholder secret name + key — confirm the
exact name against your release):

```sh
# Secret name is derived from the machine Username ('iam-admin') by the chart.
kubectl get secret <project-name>-zitadel-iam-admin \
  -o jsonpath='{.data.pat}' | base64 -d > /tmp/zitadel-pat   # do NOT commit
PAT="$(cat /tmp/zitadel-pat)"
```

## Register the OIDC client application (Admin / Management API)

Use the machine-user PAT to create an OIDC application under a project. The
Management API endpoint (verified LIVE 2026-06-02 — `proto/zitadel/management.proto`
`rpc AddOIDCApp`, evidence.md P-19) is:

```
POST /management/v1/projects/{project_id}/apps/oidc
Authorization: Bearer <pat>
```

Example (placeholders — `<zitadel-instance-url>`, `<project-id>`, `$PAT`):

```sh
curl -fsSL -X POST \
  "https://<zitadel-instance-url>/management/v1/projects/<project-id>/apps/oidc" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer ${PAT}" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{
    "name": "<project-name>-web",
    "redirectUris": ["http://127.0.0.1:8123/auth/callback"],
    "responseTypes": ["OIDC_RESPONSE_TYPE_CODE"],
    "grantTypes": ["OIDC_GRANT_TYPE_AUTHORIZATION_CODE"],
    "appType": "OIDC_APP_TYPE_WEB",
    "authMethodType": "OIDC_AUTH_METHOD_TYPE_NONE",
    "accessTokenType": "OIDC_TOKEN_TYPE_JWT"
  }'
```

**Compliance note**: in dev the OIDC client MUST use a **loopback / internal**
redirect URI (e.g. `http://127.0.0.1:8123/auth/callback`, matching the compose
fragment's loopback bind). Production redirect URIs require adopter configuration
(public hostname + HTTPS). The returned `clientId` (and `clientSecret` for
confidential apps) is a secret — store it in a K8s Secret, never in the repo.

## JWT signing-key rotation (FR-B87-027)

Zitadel **manages JWT signing keys internally — automatic rotation, no operator
duty by default** (verified LIVE 2026-06-02, `cmd/defaults.yaml`, evidence.md P-20):

- **Rotation lifetimes** — `SystemDefaults.KeyConfig`
  (env `ZITADEL_SYSTEMDEFAULTS_KEYCONFIG_*`):
  - `PrivateKeyLifetime: 6h` — signing key rotated every 6 hours.
  - `PublicKeyLifetime: 30h` — public (verification) key retained 30 hours so
    in-flight tokens validate across rotations.
- **WebKeys** — `DefaultInstance.WebKeys`: OIDC token signing keys are generated
  when a new instance is created; default `Type: rsa`, `RSABits: 2048`,
  `RSAHasher: sha256` (ECDSA P256 also available).
- **Explicit rotation**: the WebKeys v2 management API
  (`proto/zitadel/webkey/v2/webkey_service.proto`) supports operator-triggered
  rotation if a policy requires it.

No manual rotation is required for the default posture; relying parties fetch the
current keys from the JWKS endpoint (`/oauth/v2/keys`) and tolerate rotation via
the 30h public-key overlap.

## Secrets posture recap (ADR-B87-004)

- **Masterkey** — pre-created K8s Secret, referenced by `masterkeySecretName` in
  `values-forge.yaml.tmpl`; "Must be exactly 32 bytes" (P-06). Value never committed.
- **DB DSN** — pre-created K8s Secret, referenced via `valueFrom.secretKeyRef`
  (DSN mode); the connection string (with password) is never committed.
- **Machine-user PAT** — auto-generated by the chart `setupJob` into a K8s Secret;
  read at deploy time, never committed.
- **OIDC client secret** (confidential apps) — returned by the Admin API call
  above; store in a K8s Secret, never in the repo.
